ry few weeks.<br>
<br>
Playing style also effects things a great deal.  Take the numerous statements by skilled <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Magicians</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> that they can control their pets <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><u>anywhere</u><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END-->, in contrast to numerous reports of places where it is claimed that bad pathing disallows pets.  Or the ease with one player controls aggro, where another does not.  <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Damage Logs</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> may be suspect if the play involved is abnormal or sub-par.<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> Analysis of log data can help us find reasonable values...<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->Ah, but there's a <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><u>world</u><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> of assumptions behind those relationships, and they must at the very least be made explicit so we can state the limits of what that analysis tells us.   How can you measure the utility of <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Gate</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> and <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Bind</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, or compare that to the ability to sustain melee?<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> So yes, you're right, I don't think Verant is that worried about soloing better.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->I guess I am either cautious or pessimistic, but based on what I have seen <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Verant</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> in the past, I conclude that they <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><u>will</u><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> us those to form bounds on what is acceptable to them.<br>
<br>
I would rather anticipate and attempt to answer their objections in advance than simply pray for the best, and discover that when we open up our <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Christmas</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> presents, they're nothing but socks and <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Garfield</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> calenders.<br>
