This is part of why I like improving pet damage output more.  Making them indifferent can easily cause problems.  I can solo green areas to farm items now because if anything agros me, I can just train the pet: they hate it too.<br>
<br>
If the pet is indifferent, it may not be trainable, which may simply get us killed <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>  more</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->.<br>
<br>
Putting the pets on a new combat table seems like it would be easier and safer.  I'm also not sure how you can say that our high end damage output is good... the logs that have been posted here seem pretty agreeable that if you're the second mage and cannot factor in damage shields, your damage output even with an epic pet is poor.  Even with the damage shield it's a fair margin below monk damage output.  Given our poor utility and complete lack of defense, I find it unreasonable that our maximum long term damage output under ideal conditions is still less than that of a monk.<br>
<br>
I think that increasing pet damage is the best solution all around.<br>
<br>
And frankly, if it improves our soloability, so what?  I haven't done a detailed study, but I think it's quite possible that an epic shadowknight can outsolo us now.  With their highest pet (level 44 necro summons), the lifedrain proc of their epic plus their ability to fear and dark, they can handily solo things that are too powerful for magicians, and never have to worry about losing 50% XP in the process, and there's less downtime on top of that!  (There's a 60 SK in my old guild that solo's Skyfire for AA points and spells.  Dark+fear+pet+melee yields great damage output and safety, and the proc on his epic is enough to heal the damage he takes reapplying fears.  Couldn't say for sure if he outsolos a mage, but I can't imagine how that couldn't be true.  Point being, we're low enough on the soloing foodchain now that &quot;incidentally&quot; kicking us up a notch or two wouldn't break the game.)<br>
