<br>
Now if mage+pet = rogue damage, suddenly there's more justification for the risk.<br>
<br>
A lot of raid leaders don't allow pets simply because it's not worth it.  You may be the best pet handler in the world, they may know it, but frequently they <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> still</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> won't let you use the pet out of sheer paranoia and the fact that they pet doesn't really contribute anything they need.<br>
<br>
It's the difference between:<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Today</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
Marginal usefulness, minimal risk<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Post-Patch</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
Excellent usefulness, minimal risk<br>
<br>
Today it's not worth it, post-patch?  Maybe it will be.<br>
<br>
And frankly, I think this is our justification for being the #1 damage class.  More than wizards, more than rogues.  Wizards are a safe bet: you stick them in the back of the bus and they blow stuff up.  If we're going to risk disaster by sending a numbskull pet into the fray with bad pathing, it <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> should</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> do a whole shitload of damage.<br>
<br>
Risk vs Reward.<br>
<br>
Keep pets as high risk, but make using them be high reward.<br>
