I would not complain if Verant did increase pet strength (and they might, with additional changes). Want increased pet strength? Are you willing to accept a refresh timer on your pet, or a mana cost of 500-600 mana per pet post-50? A refresh timer might not be such a hot idea since a mage can just mem all 4 pets and rotate. Increased mana cost for increased damage.. that might fly, though.<br>
<br>
Though, I think you misstate the 'minimal risk'. Risk is usually dependant on the area you're in. In a place where much mezzing is to be done (Ex: PoA, second island), a loose pet (no matter his damage output) == dead enchanter. Dead enchanter == fiercer fight, and quite possibly a wipeout. Teleporting mobs, Scarelings and the like.. Yonder a pet, say g'bye to the raid. Now, AoE mobs and the like (depending on the raid leader's tactics) might be doable, in like ToV, but there's always the issue of 'aggro radius' between a pet of level.. 41-45 (Vocerate) and PC's of 55+ in level. And then there's pathing. Path takes pet away then back to target mob, pet now has 3 more buddies due to his choice of directions. <br>
<br>
To add to technical issues, there's also a ton of social issues for why pets aren't permitted. Those, unfortunately, Verant can only state facts on and hope that others listen. The 4 pet rumor, and Dire Charm pets. Aggro management. That sort of thing. Even if you're the best at controlling your pet, you still have to prove it time and again, and even then, your skill might get ignored, or fluffed off as 'well, that's fine HERE, but in &lt;Raid Zone a&gt;, it wouldn't work still'.<br>
<br>
You want to increase the reward for using a pet. That's great. The reward, I doubt, would still cumulate into an overwhelming shift from forbidden pets to wanted pets, since the risks have not changed, and so far, most people have gotten along just fine without pets. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub6.ezboard.com/ubalanzsonofanz.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Balanz son of Anz</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Abuser of EZCodes</span><br>  Posts: 782<br> <font color=#333333>(2/8/02 11:34:11 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowerfrm32.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=82.topic&index=30>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_exclamation_mark.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Increased Pet Strength, Summary Pro and Con</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> REPOST due to browser issues.</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Rhasin:</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->  VI seems to think that at higher end, we do not need to deal as much damage as before. In most cases, this tends to be accurate, because of the tendancy for raids to be melee heavy.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->But this is <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><u>precisely</u><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> the problem.  As I have argued elsewhere, once sufficient support is available, additional support is marginal while additional damage dealer stack well.  This is exactly <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><u>why</u><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> raids are melee heavy, and only a few lucky players from each support class are welcome.  I believe that the <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><u>third</u><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> and subsequent <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Magicians</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> on a raid should be about as valuable as a melee.  And that means damage dealing.<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Wezloc:</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->  Now that Verant seems to be focusing on the new server I think all class improvements will be pushed to the back burner. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->This is exactly what I fear as well.  <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Verant</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> has already stated that they are far more interested in developing new content than fixing old content, and <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Legends</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> is the ultimate sink for new content.  It is up to <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Verant</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> to disprove by the actions the impression that development time spent on <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Legends</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> will not be taken from that spent on their existing customers.<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Wezloc:</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->  But even though I think indifferent pets are the easiest upgrades for them to make, it also takes away all the risk for using a pet.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->  Once upon a time, when I could hand a <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Warrior</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> his ass to him on a plate, all while I sat on mine, that was appropriate.  But consider this <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><u>hallowed</u><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> principal: <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Risk Versus Reward</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->.  Is the reward really all that great, nowadays?  What is the risk of a 40% haste belt, <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><u>once obtained</u><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END-->?  The only cost is what else you might wear.<br>
<br>
There are two prices to pay for something generally, initial costs and maintanance.  All the power that has rained down upon <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Melees</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> like the joyous tears of <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Karana</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> may have a high initial cost, taking the effort of a guild in a dangerous raid, but there is no maintanence cost.  In contrast, <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Magicians</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> take the lives of the comrades into their hands every time they summon a pet in uncertain circumstances.  From a <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Risk versus Reward</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> standpoint, I could just as easily argue that <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Elementals</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> should kick unholy butt given the risk they bring.<br>
<br>
The only other players who directly threaten to kill the entire raid are the pullers, and the crowd control, and the rewards are comensurately great.  In contrast, pets are neither vital, nor worth the risk of wipeout.<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Wezloc:</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->  ...sees a pet attacking one of his buddies will...<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->Social foes, which are most spawns, will come to the aid of their friends, regardless of faction.  Faction determines the initial attitude towards the pet, until the pet attacks something.<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Grumples:</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->  If the pet is indifferent, it may not be trainable, which may simply get us killed more.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> /pet attack</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> is good enough for me, and I am happy that <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Indifferent Pets</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> has some compensating costs.<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Grumples:</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->  I'm also not sure how you can say that our high end damage output is good...<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->I have not analyzed damage output in detail.  My conclusion is based first, on my experience, and second, on a reading of the logs.  It is reinforced by the notion that <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Verant</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> considers pets already to be over-powering, and so any increases in damage output will likely be limited.  However, this idea is supported by a large number of <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Magicians</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, and deserves my support for that reason.<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> Point being, we're low enough on the soloing foodchain now that &quot;incidentally&quot; kicking us up a notch or two wouldn't break the game.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->This is my point of view, but as the empty cardboard box says, <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> &quot;You're in <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><u>our</u><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> world now.&quot;</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->  As <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Verant</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> has stated that they consider us to be over-powered at soloing, I assume that they will continue to see us in that light, and will consider the impact of soloing of our proposed remedies.<br>
<br>
Perhaps the <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Development Team</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> should tour the universe, see what players are actually doing on a variety of servers and zones, rather than assuming the game is as they imagine it, or as their small circle of friends plays it.<br>
<br>
For example, I am in a little race with a 59th level <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Shaman</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> named <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Wulfgarr</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->.  We each take a set of <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Sentient Armor</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> spawns.  He goes through his solo about 50% faster than I go through mine solo.<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Rhasin:</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->  What good are power upgrades if we still can't use our pets due to pathing bugs, fear, and the like?<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->Well, that is why I am in favor of <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Neutral Faction Pets</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->.  However, I fear all we may get is a rubber biscuit from <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Verant</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->.  Thus, I am trying to support as many well thought out and reasonably ambitious remedies as possible, in the hopes that if <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Verant</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> picks as chooses among them, as I suspect, there will at least be a few gems in there for them to select.  Thus, I support: <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Indifferent Pets, Increased Pet Strength,</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> and <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Reduce Pet Penalties</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->.  The shotgun approach.<br>
<br>
